04612nam a22005295i 9780804788168DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20221995cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047881687 a10.1515/97808047881682doi  a(DE-B1597)582608  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aHIS0180002bisacsh04aThe French Idea of Freedom :bThe Old Regime and the Declaration of Rights of 1789 /ced. by Dale Van Kley. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©1995  a1 online resource (452 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Making of Modern Freedom00tFrontmatter -- tSeries Foreword -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tCONTRIBUTORS -- tDeclaration of the Rights of Man and of the Citizen -- tIntroduction -- tPART I Context -- t1. Old Regime Origins of Democratic Liberty -- t2. From the Lessons of French History to Truths for All Times and All People: The Historical Origins of an Anti-Historical Declaration -- t3. Betwixt Cattle and Men: Jews, Blacks, and Women, and the Declaration of the Rights of Man -- t4. The Idea of a Declaration of Rights -- tPART II Text -- t5. National Sovereignty and the General Will: The Political Program of the Declaration of Rights -- t6. Safeguarding the Rights of the Accused: Lawyers and Political Trials in France, 1716-1789 -- t7. Religious Toleration and Freedom of Expression -- t8. Property, Sovereignty, the Declaration of the Rights of Man, and the Tradition of French Jurisprudence -- tGlossary -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a“The Declaration of the Rights of Man and the Citizen of 1789” is the French Revolution’s best known utterance. By 1789, to be sure, England looked proudly back to the Magna Carta, the Petition of Right, and a bill of rights, and even the young American Declaration of Independence and the individual states’ various declarations and bills of rights preceded the French Declaration. But the French deputies of the National Assembly tried hard, in the words of one of their number, not to receive lessons from others but rather “to give them” to the rest of the world, to proclaim not the rights of Frenchmen, but those “for all times and nations.” The chapters in this book treat mainly the origins of the Declaration in the political thought and practice of the preceding three centuries that Tocqueville designated the “Old Regime.” Among the topics covered are privileged corporations; the events of the three months preceding the Declaration; blacks, Jews, and women; the Assembly’s debates on the Declaration; the influence of sixteenth-century notions of sovereignty and the separation of powers; the rights of the accused in legal practices and political trials from 1716 to 1789; the natural rights to freedom of religion; and the monarchy’s “feudal” exploitation of the royal domain.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 4aHistory -- European. 4aHistory -- Intellectual and Cultural. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Ireland.2bisacsh1 aBaker, Keith Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBien, David D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaiser, Thomas E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKley, Dale Van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSingham, Shanti Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVan Kley, Dale, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVan Kley, Dale, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080478816840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804788168423Coveruhttps://www.degruyt